      <p>If you are selling a unit in a Brisbane body corporate building, one question will almost certainly come up during your campaign: does the building allow Airbnb or other short-term letting platforms? For some buyers this is a dealbreaker one way or the other. Understanding your building's position before you list, and knowing how to disclose it, will help you attract the right buyers and avoid problems during the contract period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How body corporate by-laws regulate short-stay letting</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, a community titles scheme is governed by a set of by-laws registered with the body corporate. By-laws cover the rules that apply to all lots in the scheme: noise, pets, parking, renovations, common property use, and, increasingly, short-term letting. Whether Airbnb is permitted in your building is determined entirely by what the by-laws say.</p>

      <p>The range of positions varies considerably across Brisbane buildings. Some have by-laws that explicitly prohibit short-term letting in any form. Others restrict it with conditions, requiring minimum stays, a guest register, or approval from the committee. Some buildings have no restriction on short-stay at all. And some older buildings have by-laws that predate platforms like Airbnb and make no specific mention of short-term letting, leaving the position legally unclear.</p>

      <p>To find out what your building's by-laws say, contact the body corporate manager. They hold a current copy of the registered by-laws and can tell you precisely what is and is not permitted. This is information worth obtaining before you list, not after a buyer asks.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why this matters to owner-occupier buyers</h2>
      <p>Owner-occupiers often have strong preferences about whether their building allows short-term letting. A building that permits unrestricted Airbnb means a constant rotation of short-stay guests: different people in the lift every weekend, strangers using the pool and common areas, and a general sense of impermanence in the building. Many owner-occupiers find this undesirable, particularly in smaller complexes where the residents know each other and the building has a stable community feel.</p>

      <p>If your building allows unrestricted short-stay and this is known to the market, you may find the pool of owner-occupier buyers smaller than you expected. That is not necessarily a catastrophic outcome, but it is worth understanding upfront so your pricing and marketing strategy reflects it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why this matters to investor buyers</h2>
      <p>Investors buying for short-stay income purpose have the opposite concern. They specifically need a building where short-term letting is permitted by the by-laws. A by-law that prohibits Airbnb is an absolute dealbreaker for a buyer whose entire investment thesis depends on short-stay returns. No matter how attractive the unit or the price, a prohibition makes the purchase impossible for that buyer profile.</p>

      <p>Conversely, if your building explicitly permits short-term letting, that is a feature for the investor buyer pool. Buildings with clear, permissive short-stay by-laws attract a specific segment of buyers who are willing to pay a premium for the certainty that their intended use is legally supported.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Queensland legal framework</h2>
      <p>Queensland body corporate schemes are regulated under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997 and the associated regulation modules. The Act sets out what body corporates can and cannot do in governing their schemes, and it defines the process for creating, amending, and enforcing by-laws.</p>

      <p>There has been ongoing legal debate in Queensland, as in other states, about the extent to which a body corporate can validly prohibit short-term letting through a by-law. Some older blanket prohibition by-laws have been challenged at the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal and in court. The question of enforceability can be complex, particularly for buildings with older by-laws that were not specifically drafted with platforms like Airbnb in mind.</p>

      <p>This is not a simple area of law, and sellers should not assume that because a by-law exists, it is necessarily enforceable. If your building has a by-law that restricts or prohibits short-term letting and a buyer is specifically asking about enforceability, direct them to their own solicitor. The question goes beyond what a real estate agent can or should answer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How sellers should disclose to buyers</h2>
      <p>If your building has a by-law that addresses short-term letting in any way, disclosing it clearly and early is the right approach. Buyers who discover a by-law restriction after signing a contract, during the due diligence period, are the most likely to renegotiate price or seek to withdraw. A surprise of this kind damages the sale and your relationship with the buyer at exactly the moment you need their confidence to be highest.</p>

      <p>The by-laws form part of the body corporate disclosure statement, which sellers of Queensland units are required to provide to buyers before contracts are exchanged. The buyer's solicitor will also obtain the by-laws through the records search. Either way, the information will come out. The question is whether it comes out on your terms, early and clearly, or whether the buyer discovers it in week two of their due diligence and starts to wonder what else was not mentioned.</p>

      <p>A proactive disclosure approach, telling buyers what the by-laws say before they ask, is both legally sound and commercially smart. It attracts buyers whose intentions match the building's rules and filters out buyers for whom the by-laws would be a dealbreaker. The resulting pool of buyers is smaller but more serious.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do before listing</h2>
      <p>Before you take your unit to market, do three things. First, obtain a current copy of the by-laws from the body corporate manager and read the provisions relating to letting, subletting, and short-term occupancy. Second, ask the body corporate manager directly whether there are any current or pending changes to the by-laws on this topic. By-laws can be amended at a general meeting, and a proposed change may not yet be reflected in the current registered version. Third, if your building's position is ambiguous or contested, seek your own legal advice before answering buyer questions about it.</p>

      <p>The more clearly you understand your building's position before you list, the better placed you are to attract the right buyers and navigate the due diligence period without surprises.</p>

